Here is the full **testsmells.org 19-smell catalog** audit of your integration tests, with integration-test calibration applied.

---

## Summary Dashboard

```
┌──────────┬─────────────┬────────────────┐
│ Severity │ Smell Count │ Affected Tests │
├──────────┼─────────────┼────────────────┤
│ High     │ 3           │ 3              │
│ Medium   │ 1           │ 1              │
│ Low      │ 0           │ 0              │
│ Total    │ 4           │ 4              │
└──────────┴─────────────┴────────────────┘
```

4 of 8 test methods are smell-free. The remaining 4 carry findings across 4 distinct smell categories.

---

## HIGH Severity Findings

### 1. Sleepy Test — `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` (line 87)

`Thread.Sleep(3000)` introduces a hard 3-second wall-clock wait. This makes the suite slow and non-deterministic — if the notification mechanism takes 3.1 seconds on a loaded CI agent, the test flakes.

**Integration-test calibration:** Even for integration tests, `Thread.Sleep` is a smell. Async coordination should use polling/signaling, not fixed delays.

```csharp
// ❌ Current
Thread.Sleep(3000);
Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id));

// ✅ Fix — poll with a timeout
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
while (!_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id))
{
    await Task.Delay(100, cts.Token);
}
Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id));
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Flaky CI failures; suite gets slower as more sleepy tests accumulate.

---

### 2. Conditional Test Logic — `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` (lines 101–108)

An `if/else` branch means **only one path ever executes** per run. If `loaded` is never a `PremiumUser`, the `DiscountRate > 0` assertion is dead code — silently untested.

```csharp
// ❌ Current
if (loaded is PremiumUser premium)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(premium.DiscountRate > 0);
}
else
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded!.Name);
}

// ✅ Fix — split into two deterministic tests
[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_StandardUser_ReturnsCorrectName()
{
    _repository.Insert(new User("eve@example.com", "Eve"));
    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com");
    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded.Name);
}

[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_PremiumUser_HasDiscount()
{
    _repository.Insert(new PremiumUser("prem@example.com", "Prem", 0.1m));
    var loaded = (PremiumUser)_repository.GetByEmail("prem@example.com")!;
    Assert.IsTrue(loaded.DiscountRate > 0);
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Hidden testing gap — one branch may never execute, giving false coverage.

---

### 3. Assertion-Free Test (Unknown Test) — `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` (lines 112–119)

This method exercises `Insert` 100 times but **never asserts anything**. MSTest reports it as passing even if every insert silently fails (e.g., swallows exceptions internally).

The name `_RunsWithoutErrors` suggests a "does not throw" intent, but without an explicit assertion the test provides false confidence.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — no assertions at all
for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
{
    _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
}

// ✅ Fix — verify the side effect
for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
{
    _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
}
var users = _repository.ListAll();
Assert.AreEqual(100, users.Count);
```

**Risk if unfixed:** False pass — broken inserts go completely undetected.

---

## MEDIUM Severity Findings

### 4. Assertion Roulette — `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` (lines 35–38)

Four assertions with **no descriptive messages**. When one fails, the MSTest output shows only `Assert.AreEqual failed` — you must read the code to determine which property was wrong.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — no messages
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name);
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email);
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0);

// ✅ Fix — add assertion messages
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded, "User should be retrievable after insert");
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name, "Name should be persisted");
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email, "Email should be persisted");
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0, "Id should be assigned on insert");
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Slower failure diagnosis in CI logs; developers waste time reproducing locally to identify which property failed.

---

## Smells Scanned — No Findings (15 of 19 clean)

| Smell | Status | Notes |
|-------|--------|-------|
| Mystery Guest | ✅ Clean | In-memory SQLite — not an external resource |
| Eager Test | ✅ Clean | No test calls 4+ distinct production methods |
| Magic Number Test | ✅ Clean | All numeric literals (3, 10, 100) are contextually obvious |
| Sensitive Equality | ✅ Clean | No `ToString()` in assertions |
| Exception Handling | ✅ Clean | No `try/catch` in tests |
| General Fixture | ✅ Clean | Both fields used by all 8 tests |
| Ignored/Disabled Test | ✅ Clean | No `[Ignore]` attributes |
| Duplicate Assert | ✅ Clean | No identical assertion pairs |
| Lazy Test | ✅ Clean | Each test targets a distinct behavior |
| Constructor Init. | ✅ Clean | Uses `[TestInitialize]` correctly |
| Default Test | ✅ Clean | Class name is descriptive |
| Redundant Print | ✅ Clean | No print/console statements |
| Redundant Assertion | ✅ Clean | No tautological assertions |
| Resource Optimism | ✅ Clean | No assumed external files/services |
| Empty Test | ✅ Clean | All methods contain executable code |

---

## Smell-Free Tests Worth Highlighting

`UpdateUser_ModifiesExistingRecord`, `DeleteUser_RemovesFromDatabase`, `ListUsers_ReturnsAllInserted`, and `InsertUser_ConcurrentInserts_MaintainsIntegrity` are well-structured: clear arrange/act/assert, focused scope, and self-documenting assertions.

---

## Prioritized Remediation Plan

| Priority | Smell | Fix | Effort |
|----------|-------|-----|--------|
| 1 | **Assertion-Free Test** | Add count assertion to `BulkInsert` | ~2 min |
| 2 | **Conditional Test Logic** | Split `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` into 2 tests | ~5 min |
| 3 | **Sleepy Test** | Replace `Thread.Sleep` with polling loop | ~10 min |
| 4 | **Assertion Roulette** | Add message strings to 4 assertions | ~3 min |

Start with #1 — it takes two minutes and eliminates a false-pass risk. All four fixes together are roughly 20 minutes of work.
